# Git Workflow

## Commit Message Format
`type(scope): description`

Types:
- `feat` — new functionality
- `fix` — bug fix
- `chore` — tooling, config, scaffolding
- `test` — adding or fixing tests
- `docs` — documentation only
- `refactor` — restructuring without behavior change

Examples:
- `feat(routing): add Dijkstra engine with PathResult schema`
- `fix(inventory): handle zero-rowcount decrement as False`
- `chore: handoff to cursor — phase 1 complete`

## Commit Discipline
- One logical change per commit — not one file per commit
- Commit after each completed task, before switching tools
- Never commit with failing tests
- Never commit `.env` — only `.env.example`
  > WHY: Small commits make rollback surgical. The Git boundary is the handoff point between Claude Code and Cursor.

## Dual-Agent Handoff Protocol
- Claude Code finishes a phase → updates `TODO.md` → commits → Cursor picks up
- Cursor finishes a module → marks `TODO.md` checkbox → commits → returns to Claude Code
- Commit message for handoffs: `chore: handoff to cursor — phase N complete`
  > WHY: Clean commit = clean state = no merge conflicts between tools.

## TODO.md Sync
- After implementing each file, mark its checkbox `[x]` in `TODO.md`
- Update `TODO.md` in the same commit as the implementation
  > WHY: `TODO.md` is the single source of truth for sprint progress. Stale checkboxes mislead the next agent.
